TY  - JOUR
T1  - Communications: Comment: “The Impact on Managers of Frequency of Feedback”— By Doris M. Cook
AU  - Shenson, Howard L.
Y1  - 1969/03/01
PY  - 1969
DA  - 1969/03/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.1969.27448056
DO  - 10.5465/amj.1969.27448056
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 119
EP  - 121
VL  - 12
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article comments on the paper ?The Impact on Managers of Frequency of Feedback,? by Doris M. Cook. The article is believed to be an example of over reliance on the obvious and a failure to control or test for relevant variables. For a long time, management theorists have argued that frequent feedback has a positive impact on the communication process and the effectiveness of an organization. Cook's findings may be significant because they correlate with several external variable. However, correlation only implies a relationship and not causality.
AB  - This article comments on the paper ?The Impact on Managers of Frequency of Feedback,? by Doris M. Cook. The article is believed to be an example of over reliance on the obvious and a failure to control or test for relevant variables. For a long time, management theorists have argued that frequent feedback has a positive impact on the communication process and the effectiveness of an organization. Cook's findings may be significant because they correlate with several external variable. However, correlation only implies a relationship and not causality.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amj.1969.27448056
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amj.1969.27448056
Y2  - 2026/04/24
